          "role": "user",
          "content": "What are my rights during arrest?",
          "language": "en",
          "createdAt": "2026-06-11T14:36:32.034205"
        },
        {
          "role": "assistant",
          "content": "When you are being arrested under the BNSS, you have specific protections to ensure your fundamental rights are respected:\n\n*   **Right to be informed:** You must be immediately informed of the exact grounds for your arrest and your right to be released on bail if the offense is bailable.\n*   **Right to notify a person:** You have the right to have a friend, relative, or any person of your choice informed about your arrest and your location.\n*   **Right to legal assistance:** You are entitled to meet with an advocate of your choice during your interrogation, though not necessarily throughout the entire duration of the questioning.\n*   **Medical examination:** You have the right to be examined by a medical officer immediately after your arrest, and a record of your health condition must be maintained.\n*   **Right to remain silent:** While you must provide your name and address, you have the right to remain silent regarding incriminating questions to avoid self-incrimination.\n*   **Presence of an officer:** You have the right to be arrested by a police officer who is wearing a clear, visible, and legible identification of their name and designation.\n\nTo give you more specific advice, are you currently facing an arrest, or are you asking for future awareness?\n\n*Disclaimer: This information is for educational purposes and does not constitute formal legal advice; please consult with an advocate for your specific situation.*",
