        {
          "role": "assistant",
          "content": "I am very sorry to hear about your experience. Being robbed near your home is a traumatic event, and your sense of safety is paramount. As an AI Legal Assistant, I have synthesized the relevant legal information to help you understand the process and the steps you should take next.\n\n***\n\n### 1. Immediate Action Required: Filing an FIR\nThe most critical step is to report the incident to the police immediately. Under **Section 173 of the Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita (BNSS)**, you have the right to file a First Information Report (FIR).\n\n*   **How to file:** Visit your nearest police station. You can provide the information orally or in writing.\n*   **Essential:** Ensure the FIR is read back to you once written, and verify all details before signing it. Always request a free copy of the FIR for your records.\n*   **Urgency:** The sooner you report, the higher the chance of securing time-sensitive evidence like CCTV footage or tracking data.\n\n### 2. Legal Classification\nUnder the **Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita (BNS)**, your incident is classified under **Section 309 (Robbery)**.\n*   **Definition:** This section applies when theft is committed or attempted while causing—or threatening to cause—death, hurt, or wrongful restraint to a person.\n*   **Penalty:** This is a serious offense; upon conviction, the perpetrator can face imprisonment for up to 10 years and a fine of up to ₹1,00,000.\n\n### 3. Evidence to Assist the Investigation\nTo strengthen your case, the police will need to collect evidence. You can assist them by noting down or providing the following:\n*   **Visuals:** Any nearby CCTV footage (from your home, neighbors, or street cameras).\n*   **Testimony:** Any witnesses who may have seen the incident or the perpetrator.\n*   **Digital Data:** If your phone was stolen, provide the IMEI number and any tracking data (e.g., Google/Apple \"Find My\" location history).\n*   **Physical Items:** If any items were left behind by the perpetrator or if you noticed specific physical traits (height, clothing, vehicle registration, etc.).\n\n### 4. Overview of the Legal Timeline (BNSS)\nUnderstanding the journey of a criminal case can help manage expectations:\n\n1.  **Investigation (Section 176 BNSS):** The police will gather evidence, record statements, and perform search/seizures over the next 60 to 90 days.\n2.  **Police Report/Charge Sheet (Section 193 BNSS):** Once the investigation is complete, the police will submit a final report to the Magistrate.\n3.  **Cognizance & Committal (Sections 210 & 262 BNSS):** The Magistrate takes note of the case and, because robbery is a serious offense, sends it to the Court of Session for trial.\n4.  **Framing of Charge & Trial (Sections 251–260 BNSS):** The Judge formally states the charges against the accused. The trial follows, where the prosecution presents evidence, and the defense is given an opportunity to respond.\n5.  **Judgment (Section 392 BNSS):** After the trial concludes, the Judge will deliver a verdict of conviction or acquittal.\n\n***\n\n### Support and Safety Recommendations\n*   **Prioritize Wellbeing:** Please reach out to friends, family, or a counselor if you are feeling overwhelmed. Trauma after a robbery is a natural reaction.\n*   **Documentation:** Keep a file containing a copy of your FIR, the name of the Investigating Officer (IO), and a list of all items stolen.\n*   **Follow-ups:** If you do not receive updates, you have the right to follow up with the Investigating Officer at the police station regarding the status of the investigation.\n\n***\n\n**Disclaimer:** *I am an AI, not a lawyer. This information is for educational purposes and does not constitute formal legal advice. Given the severity of this incident, I strongly recommend consulting with a local criminal defense attorney or a public prosecutor to guide you through the specific nuances of your case.*",
