          "role": "user",
          "content": "What are my rights during arrest?",
          "language": "en",
          "createdAt": "2026-06-17T09:50:31.399178"
        },
        {
          "role": "assistant",
          "content": "Under Indian law, you have several fundamental rights during an arrest, which are designed to protect your liberty and ensure due process. These rights are primarily enshrined in the Constitution of India and detailed in the Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita, 2023 (BNSS), which is set to replace the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973.\n\nHere are your key rights during an arrest:\n\n1.  **Right to be Informed of the Grounds of Arrest (BNSS Section 35(1)(a) & Article 22(1) of the Constitution):** You have the right to be immediately informed of the precise reasons for your arrest and the specific offence for which you are being apprehended.\n2.  **Right to be Informed of the Right to Bail (BNSS Section 35(1)(b)):** If you are arrested for a bailable offence, you must be informed that you have a right to be released on bail upon furnishing a bond, and arrangements can be made to secure your release.\n3.  **Right to Legal Representation (BNSS Section 35(1)(e) & Article 22(1) of the Constitution):** You have the fundamental right to consult with and be defended by a legal practitioner of your choice from the moment of arrest. If you cannot afford a lawyer, you are entitled to free legal aid provided by the State.\n4.  **Right to be Produced Before a Magistrate (BNSS Section 35(2) & Article 22(2) of the Constitution):** You cannot be detained for more than 24 hours (excluding the time necessary for the journey from the place of arrest to the Magistrate's court) without being produced before a Judicial Magistrate.\n5.  **Right to Inform a Relative/Friend (BNSS Section 35(1)(c)):** You have the right to have a relative, friend, or any other person nominated by you, informed of your arrest and the place where you are being held. The police are obligated to communicate this information to your nominated person without unnecessary delay.\n6.  **Right to Remain Silent (BNSS Section 43(1) & Article 20(3) of the Constitution):** You cannot be compelled to be a witness against yourself. While you should cooperate with the investigation, you are not obligated to make self-incriminating statements. Any confession made to a police officer while in custody is generally not admissible in court, except under specific circumstances provided by law.\n7.  **Right to a Medical Examination (BNSS Sections 53 & 54):** If you request it, or if there are injuries observed, you have the right to be medically examined by a registered medical practitioner. The police can also have you medically examined.\n8.  **Right to Identification of the Arresting Officer (BNSS Section 41B(a)):** The police officer making the arrest must bear accurate, visible, and clear identification of their name and designation.\n9.  **Right to an Arrest Memo (BNSS Section 41B(b)):** An arrest memo must be prepared by the police officer, attested by at least one witness (who may be a member of the family of the person arrested or a respectable person of the locality), and counter-signed by the arrested person. It should also specify the date and time of arrest.\n\n---\n**Note:** This information provides general legal guidance based on the Constitution of India and the Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita, 2023 (BNSS). For specific legal advice concerning your individual circumstances, it is always recommended to consult with a qualified legal professional.",
          "language": "en",
