          "content": "### ⚖️ Incident Classification & Severity\n\n**Category:** Theft\n\n**Severity:** High (Score: 85)\n\n**Urgency:** Prompt reporting is crucial, ideally within hours of discovery, to maximize the chances of recovery and mitigate data security risks.\n\n### 📚 Applicable Legal Sections\n\n- **BNS Section 303 - Theft**: Whoever intends to take any movable property out of the possession of any person without that person's consent, in order to such property wrongfully to use it, is said to commit theft. *(Punishment: Imprisonment up to 3 years and/or fine up to ₹10,000)*\n- **BNS Section 304 - Snatching**: Theft is snatching if the offender suddenly or quickly or forcibly seizes or secures or grabs or takes away from any person the movable property. *(Punishment: Imprisonment up to 3 years and fine.)*\n- **BNS Section 305 - Theft in dwelling house, vehicle, etc.**: Whoever commits theft in any building, tent or vessel used as a human dwelling, or for custody of property; or of any vehicle, vessel, or place of worship. *(Punishment: Imprisonment up to 7 years and fine.)*\n- **IPC Section 379 - Theft**: Whoever, intending to take dishonestly any movable property out of the possession of any person without that person's consent. *(Punishment: Imprisonment up to 3 years and/or fine.)*\n\n### 🗂️ Recommended Evidence & Documents\n\n**Evidence Needed:**\n- Original ID Proof of the complainant (e.g., Aadhar Card, PAN Card, Voter ID)\n- Detailed list of the stolen laptop: Make, Model, Serial Number, Approximate Value, Purchase Date, and any unique identifying marks.\n- CCTV footage from the office premises, including entry/exit points and the specific office area, covering the timeframe of the theft.\n- Statements from potential witnesses (colleagues, security personnel, building management) who may have seen suspicious activity.\n- Proof of ownership for the laptop: Purchase invoice/bill, warranty card, or original box showing the serial number.\n- Any available tracking software details for the laptop (e.g., 'Find My Device', Prey Project, LoJack for Laptops).\n- Photographs of the office drawer/area from where the laptop was stolen, especially if there are signs of forced entry or disturbance.\n- Office access logs (e.g., swipe card data, visitor registers) for the relevant period.\n\n**Documents Needed:**\n- Valid ID Proof of the complainant (e.g., Aadhar Card, PAN Card, Voter ID)\n- Copy of the laptop's purchase invoice/bill, warranty card, or original box showing the serial number.\n- Complainant's office ID card or employment proof (if applicable).\n- Any company documents related to the laptop (if company-owned and used by the employee).\n\n### ⏳ Legal Action Roadmap\n\n- **Complaint Filing (Immediate (Day 1))**: Lodge complaint at local police station or via e-FIR. *(Ref: Section 173 BNSS)*\n- **FIR Registration (Within 3 days)**: Police register official FIR if a cognizable offense is prima facie found. *(Ref: Section 173(3) BNSS)*\n- **Investigation (Within 60-90 days)**: Police gather evidence, record statements, and identify suspects. *(Ref: Section 175-192 BNSS)*\n\n### 🏛️ Relevant Court Precedents\n\n- **State v. Raj Kumar (2023)**: Landmark judgment on what constitutes theft in digital age. Court held that unauthorized transfer of digital assets falls under theft provisions. *(Impact: Modernized theft law to cover digital assets and cryptocurrency.)*\n",
