fined extortion as the act of putting a person in fear of injury and then dishonestly compelling or inducing that person to deliver property. A crucial aspect highlighted was that the fear inflicted must be substantial enough to 'unsettle the mind' of the threatened individual. *(Impact: This judgment laid down the foundational legal framework and essential elements for understanding and prosecuting offenses related to extortion and blackmail under Indian law. It clarifies that both the act of threatening and the subsequent delivery of property induced by that fear are integral to the offense.)*\n",
